{West is to play 6\H. North leads the \DK. Perhaps you wouldn't have bid slam with East's cards, but he has been watching you pull off some fantastic squeeze plays and he has every confidence you will do it again.

You know North also has the \DQ, so your \DJ will be a Threat card against him.

And you are 99.9% sure he also has the \SA, so dummy's \SK will also be a Threat card against him.

You should be able to squeeze him in the two suits. What is your first act? 

Your first act should be to rectify the count. And the safest way to do that is to just let North hold the first trick. Who knows, he might be foolish enough to play another \D, or even to lead the \SA. Defenders do make mistakes sometimes.

But not this defender, not this time.

He exits with the \H3 which you take with your \HQ. 

Pull two more rounds of trumps, then run four \Cs, ending in your hand.

You throw a \S from dummy and North discards \Ss and \Ds. 

You are closing in. Play the \HJ, then the \H9.

Discard the \ST and \D7 from dummy.

North discards the \SQ and \S9. 

[showcards N:SK,DA,D8 E:SJ,S8,D4 S:H5,DJ,D6 W:SA,DQ,DT]

At last you play the \H5, and North is done, he just doesn't know it yet.

He obviously is not going to throw his \SA and make dummy high, so he will instead bare his \DQ.

So you dump dummy's \SK and win the last two tricks with the \DA and then the \DJ.}
[Play "W"]DK

